He remained faithful to the cause of Pompey; and at first entertained the hope that the party to which he belonged would come forth victorious from the struggle. Before the commencement of the decisive contest, he endeavored to recon- cile the two great antagonists with each other3 but at last, when every hope of preserving peace had disappeared, he followed his friend Pompey to Greece. It was in vain that many of his most distinguished and well- meaning friends cautioned him against an aet of open hostility to Caesar; for he remained firm and determined.
